The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The City Diary
                Hospitals in the city have approached the Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) for supply of filtered water. They will pay Rs 7 per 1,000 litres of water. Chief engineer (water supply) Bibhas Maity said his department will soon start supplying water to NRS Hospital. The daily requirement of the hospital will be more than 300,000 litres. RG Kar and Sambhunath Pandit hospitals have taken filtered water connection from the CMC. The state public works department is primarily responsible for supply of water to government hospitals. The state health department directed the government hospitals to approach the CMC after water supply by the PWD was disrupted.     Workers at Alliance jute mill in Barrackpore went on the rampage in the compound and allegedly beat up the personnel manager and a security officer on Sunday. Police said nearly 200 workers became infuriated after seeing a suspension of work notice around 11am. They forced their way into the administrative area of the mill and demanded their dues, said a police officer.    Rajib Chowdhury, a 25-year-old motorcyclist, was killed after being hit by a private bus on Jessore Road on Sunday afternoon. Chowdhury, a resident of Udayrajpur, in Madhyamgram, was moving towards the airport when a bus on route DN9 hit his motorcycle from the back. The youth was taken to a Madhyamgram hospital, where he was declared brought dead.    Indranil Dutta and Pratim Khanra were seriously injured when the car they were travelling in collided head-on with a truck at Ultadanga around 11.30pm on Saturday. A.K. Lahiri, the officer-in-charge of Ultadanga police station, said the driver of the truck lost control of the vehicle. The duo were taken to the ESI hospital in the vicinity.    A woman in her mid-30s was seriously injured on Sunday morning when the autorickshaw she was travelling in collided with a taxi on Gariahat Road. Residents took Snigdha Das, the injured woman, to a private hospital. Both vehicles were impounded and the drivers arrested.     A youth, identified as Sadhu, was arrested at the crossing of Paharpur Road and Ramnagar Lane on Sunday afternoon. A single-shot firearm and ammunition were found on him. Officers in plainclothes spotted Sadhu roaming suspiciously and took him into custody. A preliminary investigation revealed that he had planned to snatch valuables from pedestrians at gunpoint.    Abdul Barik Laskar was arrested in the Muchipara area early on Sunday on the charge of snatching a gold chain from a woman pedestrian. Laskar allegedly snatched the chain from Sharmila Samanta when she was walking down MG Road around 5pm on Saturday. After receiving a complaint from Samanta, officers of Muchipara police station conducted raids at several hideouts in central Calcutta. During interrogation, Laskar confessed to the crime. The chain was recovered from his possession.             
